  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV — heart rate variability — is the tiny variation in time between consecutive heartbeats. Counterintuitively, more variability is generally the good state: it suggests your nervous system is in rest-and-recover mode, while a drop below your own normal often follows hard training, poor sleep, alcohol, or oncoming illness. It's measured from continuous beat-to-beat heart data, usually overnight, which is why you don't see one: you're logging manually, and there's no sensor capturing those intervals. Your log does show last night's sleep at 456 minutes, about 7.6 h, which is a useful signal on its own. If HRV matters to you, a ring or chest strap would add it; otherwise sleep plus how you feel gets you most of the way.",
